<font color="#FF0000">NEW MEMORIAL</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jan 18 20:41:05 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
     Ah---as one who has read a lot of history, co-authored one book, and writen another, I am afraid that historical &quot;fact&quot; be in on the Crusades or Viet-Nam, is in the eye of the beholder----or author.<br><br>
    BTW, dr. is &quot;historicly correct&quot; on the same plane as &quot;politicly correct?  Coralation there somewhere.<br><br>
    I don't concur that our intentions were bad  in going to the assistance of Viet Nam as I've stated numerous times. <br><br>
  Your exploration of the impact sounds interesting, but by now,  I've come to the conclusion that the &quot;impact&quot; is over stated---by we who were directly affected by it.<br><br>
    Mostly now it appears to be reduced to these types of forums, with each of us saying: &quot;and you're another one.&quot;<br><br>
     As for me personally, as a professional, the impact has been not very personal.  No flash-backs, nightmares or even many regrets as to what I myself did while there.<br><br>
     I am deeply disappinted that not one Army gerneral resigned in protest over HOW the war was being conducted.  Shameful, from my professinal point of view.<br>
Careerism over Duty. <br>
      Dissapointed that we went back on our word and abandoned our Allies.  <br>
      Dissapointed in how my fellow soldiers were treated by their citizens apon their return.<br>
      That's about it from my limited perspective.  <br>
     I was talking with an old Amry friend of mine the other day, and he came up with a suggestion that might achieve approval from a wide range of folks on both sides of this discussion. <br><br>
      After McNamara passes on, another memorial would be constructed near the Wall.  The caskets of both LBJ and McNamara would be buried there.<br><br>
     Jutting out from the building would be a series of Piss-Tubes.  Thus after viewing the Wall one could stroll over there, unzip and show one's appreciation to those two indaviduals.<br><br>
    Not an &quot;eternal&quot; flame, perhaps, but uniquicly suited for the occaision.  I mean, they have earned a special place in our hearts.  And history.<br><br>
  Think the funds could be raised in one week-end.<br>
&quot;Warm&quot; Regards.
